sentenced to state prison for 7
to 10 years in Superior Court
Monday for the Sept. IL rifle
Staying of Georgia Davis. l9,
his common law wife.


He was found guilty of invol-
untary manslaughter on Jan. 20.
Defense attorney Walter Kessler
impressed the jury with the fact
that Montgomery S rifle was fired
accidentally. The victim was shot
twice in the head after she threat
ened to leave. Montgomery tried
to commit suicide by shooting
himself in the chest after Miss
Lewis was shot.

Ruby Hutchinson, 16, Carl Hay
den High School junior, is the
Arizona Tribune Teen of the
Week.


She is maintaining near a {
point scholastic average while
keeping active in school and
church organizations.


Ruby Is a member of the junior
National Council Of Christians
and Jews. delegate to Anytown,
a member Of the Girls League,
Badminton Club, and Standards
Committee.


A member of First Institutional
Baptist Church. she also partici-
pates in community drives such
as the Heart Fund.


She plans to be a physical
therapist and already she volun-
teers her services to help retar-
ded children.


Ruby is the daughter of Mr.. and
Mrs. Ernest Hutchinson, 25O6
West Madison.

Adult Education classes are
starting at Eastlake Park, 10th
and E. Jefferson ST., FRI, Jan.
81. Enrolment session will begin
at 10 am. in Bldg. 8.


Classes are open to any adult
regardless Of age who wishes to
improve his language or arith-
metic skills. A teacher will con-
duct all classes.


For further information con-
tact Clarence Jackson, director
262-6759, Mon. Fri, after 2 pm.
Tandem basketball free throw
tournament for elementary
school boys will be held Feb.
8 at Eastlake. Call 262-6759
for more information.


The public is invited to come
and enjoy the boys basketball
league games Mon.-Fri. E pm.
and Sat. 10 am.


Ball clinic for girls will be
held Thurs, 7 pm. All girls in
terested in playing basketball
are invited.


Senior Citizens Club meets
every first and third Wed.

Whether YOU conserve or lose
Mtamins as you trim, scrape, and
peel vegetables depends lot on
knowing where the highest con-
centrations of Wtamins are in the
various vegetables, say US. De-
partment of Agriculture nutri-
tionists.


The leafy parts of collard
greens, and kale, for example,
have much more vitan A value
than the stems or midribs do.
So, If you remove the fibrous
stems and midribs to make the
vegetables more acceptable to the
family, the loss in nutrients is
not serious.


The coarse outer leaves Of
head lettuce contain higher con-
centrations of vitamins than the
inner, tender leaves. Use the
outer leaves whenever possible.
say nutritionists of USDA's Ag-
ricultural Research Service.


When trimming cabbage, re-
member the core, as well as the
leaves. is high in vitamin c.


Broccoli leaves have much
more vitamin A than the stalks
or flower buds. If broccoli leaves
are tender when you get them
plan to eat them. Keep them cool
and moist until they re ready for
use.

If you make your own draperies
from fabric which may shrink,
it's wise to suds, rinse, and press
it before you measure and cut.


Also take advantage of the
automatic pleating tapes and
ornamental clips which give drap-
cries a custom look when hung,
and can be spread fiat for wash
ing and pressing.

WASHINGTON Undersecre-
tary of Labor John F. Henning
says unions and employers in the
construction industry would COM
ply with a new federal order de-
signed to open more jobs to Ne
groes.


Henning said field directors Of
the Brueau Of Apprenticeship and
Training had been called to Wash
1ngton and given their instruc-
lions on how to enforce the anti
discrimination directive.


Labor Secretary W. Willard
Wirtz issued the regulation. COW
ering an estimated 1000 appren-
ticeship programs, following a
Recommendation from the late
President John F. Kennedy which
took effect Friday.


Under its standards, unions
and employers must select ap-
prentices on the basis Of quail
fications and revise any WAITING
lists If necessary to remove the
impact Of previous discrimina-

Biracial primers written and
introduced by Detroit public
schools over year ago have been
rated as excellent.


DR.. Gertrude Whipple, asst.
director of language education
department, directed the plan
ming and writing process. Fol-
lett Publishing Company pre-
pared the books.


The primers tested on first
graders of various backgr ounds,
utilized white and Negro charac-
tiers and the illustrations we're
racially mixed. too.


The new books were designed
to promote social detectives as
well as reading shlls.
MAILORDER


NURSES NOT OK


NEW YORK-Mailorder schools
Of practical nursing are still
turning out would-be nurses who
can do more harm than good,
according to a survey by "Medi-
cal Tribune" physician 8
newspaper.


Lacking clinical experience,
graduates of correspondence
nursing schools are not licensed
and cannot qualify for license ex-
animation, the survey showed.
The graduates, however. wear
uniforms and other identifying
marks of the certified. licensed
practical nurse.


Physicians meeting them in
private homes may be misled
and entrust the unprofessional
with tasks they are unable to
perform.

Henning took issue with re-
port by the U. S. Civil Rights
Commission made public Monday
which suggested that such ad-
ministrative measures would not
accomplish too much.


The report said the number Of
Negro craftsmen was "alarm-

Henning said federal officials
would police the nondiscrimina-
